1.1.2 Make a function to plot ‘countplot’ if the variable is categorical and ‘distplot’ if the variable is numeric.¶

In [494]:
# get_xy() function returns position of subplots. 
#It recieves col and row index and return the 
#next one based on the two columns layout 
def get_xy(x, y):
    if y==1:
        return (x+1, 0)
    else:
        return (x, 1)
    
#arranging subplots in 2 columns and 9 rows
fig, axs = plt.subplots(nrows=9, ncols=2, figsize=(15,30))

#setting initial values of col and row index
x=0 
y=0

for i in bank_data.columns:
    if bank_data[i].dtype.name=='category':#discriminating category from other numerical dtypes
        if i=='job': # because of too long names of categories labels are rotated
            plot=sns.countplot(bank_data[i], ax=axs[x,y])
            plt.setp(plot.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45)
        else:
            sns.countplot(bank_data[i], ax=axs[x,y])
        x, y=get_xy(x, y)#getting a next values for col and row index for next subplot
    else:
        sns.distplot(bank_data[i], ax=axs[x,y])
        x, y=get_xy(x, y)

#adjustemnts of subplots arrangement in space
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.8, wspace=0.2)
plt.show()

It can be seen that ages are slightly right skewed, but not too much. Most frequent jobs are blue-collar, management and technician, and for education, most frequent is secondary. Housing is much more balanced compared to loan (taking into account that both are loans - one for housing and the other as personal loan). In fact, loan might be considered as imbalanced data. For the contact, predominant is cellular, but there is fair amount of unknown class repsresented in this varibale as well. Day and month the customer has been contacted are, more or less, evenly distributed throughout the spread of values. May is the month when most of the contacts were made, and dec, mar, oct and sep are the months when least of contacts were made. "Day" of the month is numerical (continuous) varible, however, to be consistent with "month", it may be converted to categorical. Conversion to categorical will lead to too many categories - 31. DUration and campaign show right skewness, while pdays is extremly right skewed whit great majority of values being equal to -1, rendering it as unreliable. Poutcome is highly imbalanced, having unknown class as predominant. In addition to failure and success class, there is also "other" class which does not provide clear information about success of previous marketing campaign. Target varibale is inbalanced, which might have been expected, since the aim of analysis and predictions is to increase success rate.

Based on above analysis "pdays" and "poutcome" should be removed from data set.

Now, outliers can be easily extracted from dictionary "outliers". This approach allows us to see outliers for each varibale, but also all the other variables associated with a case having an outlier

As expected, outliers lower then Q1-1.5IQR were found only in balance, while the rest were only in the area Q3+1.5IQR.

Outliers are values that falls over 3 standard deviation from the mean value and in normal distribution it would be less than 0.3% of data.

In our case numbers of outliers are as follows:

  • for age 487 (1.08%)
  • for balance 4729 (10.46%)
  • for duration 3235 (7.16%)
  • for campaign 3064 (6.78%)

If we follow more conservative approach (Chebyshev rule) - around 88.88% of data should fall within 3 standard deviation from the mean. The results are consistent with such expectations (NOTE: it has to be taken into consideration that different method for identification of outliers have been used for above numbers - IQR was used and not z score which would make such statement fully valid).

All of the outliers are eligible - there are no gross violation of common sense, e.g. age goes to 94, balance is below zero as well as above zero, duration is up to ~ 5000 seconds (around 1:40 h), and maximum number of time person was conacted is 63, however, "balance", "duration" and "campaign" are positively skewed, having significant portion of data considered as outliers, therefore those could be treated by creating bucked of values for each variable to reduce biasness for the estimation.

The above could be done using the method of equal frequency discretization. "Equal frequency binning divides the possible values of the variable into N bins, where each bin carries the same amount of observations. This is particularly useful for skewed variables as it spreads the observations over the different bins equally. Typically, we find the interval boundaries by determining the quantiles." [1]

[1] https://medium.com/towards-artificial-intelligence/outlier-detection-and-treatment-a-beginners-guide-c44af0699754

In [505]:
balance_discretised, intervals=pd.qcut(bank_data.balance, 7, labels=[1,2,3,4,5,6,7], retbins=True, precision=3, duplicates='raise')

pd.qcut function has been used for this purpose, as indicated in a code above. 7 intervals have been generated for balance with labels from 1 to 7. The amount of bins have been selected by try and test, where the idea was to get as evenly distributed data across bins as possible, while keeping the difference between those considered as outliers (bin labeled with 7) separate, as well as those that are below 0 of balance.

Similar approach has been used for the other two variables.

Afterwards, everything was recorded in a new dataframe, while removing the original related columns.

2.2. Create the training set and test set in a ratio of 70:30. Make sure and verify distribution of classes is the same in the full dataset and train test split data¶

In [534]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test=train_test_split(bank_data[bank_data.columns.drop('Target')], bank_data['Target'], test_size=0.3, random_state=7)

X_train_d, X_test_d, y_train_d, y_test_d=train_test_split(bank_data_discretised[bank_data_discretised.columns.drop('Target')], bank_data['Target'], test_size=0.3, random_state=7)

2 sets of data are prepared for training:

  • the one derived from bank_data
  • the other derived from modified version of above - bank_data_discretised.

To verify same distribution among test, train and original sets, the function is made to calculate either percentage of each class for each variable in dataframe, or mean and std if the varibale is not categorical. the result of such function is dataframe providing basic info about distribution of classes/values in given dataframe.

Function "summary_df" (described above) is fed with

  • original dataframe and
  • resulting dataframes after the split is made.

Comparison of the values has been done on all related dataframes, but also the visual representation has been provided below where distribution of classes of each varibale has been ploted against varibales. Please note, 'Target' variable has been removed from original dataframe while fed to "summary_df", to make the layout of all tree related dataframes comparable (original, train and test dataframes).

The presentation below is only done on bank_data, X_train and X_test, to reduce the size of this document.

Distribution of target varibale can be easily done by applying "summary_df" and providing as an input only bank_data['Target'] and y_train and y_test convertd to dataframe (e.g. pd.DataFrame(y_train, columns=['Target'])).

In [535]:
def summary_df(dataframe):
    summary_df=pd.DataFrame()
    for i in dataframe.columns:
        if dataframe[i].nunique()<8:
            #fdgs
            summary_df=pd.concat([summary_df, 
                                  pd.DataFrame(100*dataframe[i].value_counts()/dataframe[i].value_counts().sum())],
                                axis=1)
        else:
            dict_mean={}
            dict_mean["{0}".format(i)]=dataframe[i].mean()
            
            dict_std={}
            dict_std["{0}".format(i)]=dataframe[i].std()
            
            mean_std_df=pd.concat([pd.DataFrame(dict_mean, index=['mean']), 
                                   pd.DataFrame(dict_std, index=['std'])])
            
            summary_df=pd.concat([summary_df,
                                  mean_std_df],
                                axis=1)
            
    return summary_df

Deliverable 3 - Create the ensemble model¶

3.1 Build the ensemble models (Bagging and Boosting) and Decision Tree model (at least 4 models in total). Note the model performance by using different metrics. Use confusion matrix to evaluate class level metrics i.e. Precision/Recall¶

Models¶

4 methods have been used for training total of 8 models, each method for two models on two separate datasets generated in steps above.

Parametrisation of the models has been done based on expected/wanted outcome - in particular recall of models to be as high as possible (to gain as highest mark as possible - 5 marks for recall above 43%).

DecisionTree models were pruned with parameter max_depth equals to 6.

Random forest was trained with max_feature=10 (between two and sixtysomething) giving 10 possible fetures to be chosen from in a random fashion for each split, however, bootsrap was set to False (If False, the whole dataset is used to build each tree). It showed best results with regards to recall.

In AdaBoost and Bagging models base_estimator was used to enable class_weight parametrisation as well. This concept was lately abanodned (when tresholds have been introduced) base_estimator is simple decision tree with max_depth=2. Number of estimators (nr of trees) was left default. Even though bootstrap paramether might have been ommited for bagging models (since default value is True), it has been explicitly added to emphasize importance of it for bagging models.

In general, gini criterion was used in all models, to reduce computational time.

Predictions¶

Predictions are done based on best tresholds derived from the function best_treshold. This function searches for the optimal values of recall and precision based on f score. Recall-Precision curve has been chosen because of inbalanced data on target varibale. Since the class 0 of target variable is predominant we should not be interested in TN (higher TN is much easy to achieve compared to TP).

In [546]:
#finding the best treshold for classification
def best_treshold(model, x_test_data, y_test_data):
    prob_prediction=model.predict_proba(x_test_data)[:,1]
    prec, recall, pr_tresholds=precision_recall_curve(y_test_data, prob_prediction)
    f_score_per_tresholds=2*prec*recall/(prec+recall)
    index_of_highes_f_score=list(f_score_per_tresholds).index(max(f_score_per_tresholds))
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
    plt.title("Precission-Recall for different tresholds")
    plt.plot(recall[:-1], prec[:-1], "g", label="Precision-Recall")
    plt.plot(recall[index_of_highes_f_score], prec[index_of_highes_f_score], marker='o', color='black', label='Optimal')
    plt.xlabel("Recall")
    plt.ylabel('Precision')
    plt.legend()
    return (pr_tresholds[index_of_highes_f_score])

Prediction is calculated based on given best treshold (treshold calculated in function above). Basically the fucntion produces prediction array based on results of predict_proba fucntion of each model instance.

In [547]:
def pred_treshold_based(treshold, x_test_data, model):
    prediction=[1 if x>=treshold else 0 for x in model.predict_proba(x_test_data)[:,1]]
    return (prediction)

3.3. Explain the confusion matrix related terms like recall, precision etc. Also, select the best metric to choose one of the models from above. Give your reason for the same.¶

Explanation of confusion matrix is as follows:

  • predicted negative (0), observed negative (0) - true negative (TN) - model predicted that the customer did not subscribe term deposit and the customer realy did not subscribe term deposit; prediction was correct
  • predicted negative (0), observed positive (1) - false negative (FN) - model predicted that customer did not subscribe term deposit while the customer actually did subscribe term deposit;prediction was incorrect
  • predicted positive (1), observed positive (1) - true positive (TP) - model predicted that customer subscribed term deposit corectly; prediction was correct
  • predicted positive (1), observed negative (0) - false positive (TP) - - model predicted that customer subscribed term deposit while in reallity he/she did not; prediction was incorect

Recall gives the information how many of true positives were captured among total (observed) positives. In this context - portion of customers captured by a model, who actually subscribed term deposit.

Precision on the other hand tells how many of those captured are relevant - it measures TP against total positive predictions.

Finally, the model with best recall should be used since we don't want to miss TPs, however, even though recall is better for rf_model_d, I would recoment ab_model as it still has relativly high recall and highest precision which means not so many offers will be wasted (less money on advertising will be spent with effect compared to other models).

3.4. Answer the following questions :¶

3.4.1 What do you mean by recall and what information does it provide here?¶

Recall is caclulated from TP/(TP+FN). In this context it means a portion of subscribers who actually subscribed term deposit captured by a model. If used for a prediction it would mean that subscriber was offered a term deposit and he/she took the offer. The offer was not wasted.

3.4.2. Suggest some changes for the organization so that they can increase the number of customers who take term deposit¶

The easiest way for the orgnaisation is to increase base of the cusotmers to whom the offer of term deposit will be provided. It would easily increase number of term deposits, however, caution is advised if campaign requires financial support, since it could easily reudce effectivness of such campaign - it might increase FP as well.

3.4.5. What did you learn about banking industries from this data?¶

The most important paramter when it comes to term deposits is campaign. The wider the communication to market is, the wider the customer base with term deposit will be. From the data, the percentage of housing loans among customers is much larger compared to personal loan. Impact of the duration of contact during previous camapign is slightly correlated with subscription of term deposit.
